ses of that particular EF. As an example, the creation of a Green List Fund at a national level could support the maintenance of high management standards. It could have a governance scheme adapted to the speci\ufb01c situation in the country (Figure 8). PRIVATE INVESTORS INCOME FROM SELECTED FINANCIAL MECHANISMS DONORS NATIONAL GOVERNMENT FUNDS GREEN LIST FUND NATIONAL PARKS MEETING THE GREEN LIST STANDARD REQUIREMENTS OR ADAPT TO FIT WITH AN EXISTING EF DIRECT INVESTMENT AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE FINANCING Figure 8: The Green List Fund mechanism 41 \u2022 A source of technical experts who can work with public and private agencies to develop agile and effective management approaches; and \u2022 Capacity builders and nurturers of emerging NGOs that are becoming involved in biodiversity conservation. money to a government agency. Furthermore, the assets of an EF are almost always managed and invested by outside \ufb01nancial institutions, either inside or outside of the country \u2013 so as to provide income for the speci\ufb01c duration and speci\ufb01c purposes of that particular EF. As an example, the creation of a Green List Fund at a national level could support the maintenance of high management standards. It could have a governance scheme adapted to the speci\ufb01c situation in the country (Figure 8). PRIVATE INVESTORS INCOME FROM SELECTED FINANCIAL MECHANISMS DONORS NATIONAL GOVERNMENT FUNDS GREEN LIST FUND NATIONAL PARKS MEETING THE GREEN LIST STANDARD REQUIREMENTS OR ADAPT TO FIT WITH AN EXISTING EF DIRECT INVESTMENT AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE FINANCING Figure 8: The Green List Fund mechanism \u00a9 IUCN ELT 42 Box 11 Case Study: Fondo Mexicano para la Conservaci\u00f3n de la Naturaleza (FMCN) FMCN was established in 1994 as a non-pro\ufb01t civil association, following a three-year participatory consulting process funded by US government agencies and a number of philanthropic organisations. It is one of the largest Conservation Trust Funds (CTF) in the world, both in terms of revenues available and number of projects supported. Seed capital was provided by the US and Mexican governments and a group of US private philanthropic donors, and FMCN now manages an endowment of US$150 million, which is complemented by a stream of earmarked sinking funds raised from diverse sources at a rate of US$3-4 million per year. In 1996 FMCN was appointed manager of a separate endowment of US$16.48 million from GEF, the Fund for Natural Protected Areas (FANP).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3df2ac4a-cc04-4441-8d2a-66967d618f24": {"__data__": {"id_": "3df2ac4a-cc04-4441-8d2a-66967d618f24", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/becoming-conservation-entrepreneur", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Becoming a conservation entrepreneur", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/becoming-conservation-entrepreneur", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "565c47b9b29583faae8be44d8f6dbdb92787977b4b8e65efb18f9638fbecc10c"}, "2": {"node_id": "0bf90886-0d1a-40b7-a8d9-6222b397d416", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/becoming-conservation-entrepreneur", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "369e0cbd8ed1e8faa74dd748cc40855f53be531a18082609a2d318593b49aa5c"}}, "hash": "1897782cbc811ba0635be59eb13c09ff8f1888a9904f7cffe35dc30c33e278a4", "text": "This is not a legal entity, but a fund which is segregated from FMCN\u2019s other programmes and established to originally support 10 national protected areas. It later received further capital from GEF to include 12 additional protected areas in the programme, contingent upon one-to-one matching funds. FANP surpassed the required match, and today supports the management of 50 of Mexico\u2019s 182 protected areas with an endowment of US$106 million with the contributions of 23 donors. By covering basic operational costs of the protected areas and capacity building, FANP", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2348c289-e585-4c9b-84a5-3460b500783d": {"__data__": {"id_": "2348c289-e585-4c9b-84a5-3460b500783d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/becoming-conservation-entrepreneur", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Becoming a conservation entrepreneur", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/becoming-conservation-entrepreneur", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7d67c535b215e93eb8c8c6410137148c9bbd794578c24a22a6669211d1fee8ca"}, "3": {"node_id": "9dd2f3c8-046c-49be-a981-e0367afe868b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/becoming-conservation-entrepreneur", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7bfcaf31412bdb1f69bcfcbe8ce28f2be2d72f92eb4ace14c735023e7b38110b"}}, "hash": "ccc0722ac59a0c3c751a55afca782ea58b05d6004e52f60018d40e0ca1532088", "text": "has helped attract additional funds from both public and private sources. Furthermore, FANP has been able to customise disbursements to protected area needs, making them available at the time of the year when government resources are not. FANP provides some key lessons for setting up an environmental fund. First, it is an example of how diversi\ufb01ed revenue sources can be a source of strength \u2013 with FANP and government funding complementing each other\u2019s de\ufb01ciencies. Second, its role in encouraging stakeholder participation, particularly that of communities around the protected areas, shows how a CTF can strengthen civil society engagement in conservation. INVESTMENT AND RISK Alternatively, funding may be accessed by means of investment. Unlike donations, investments have the expectation of a return. Investors can channel funds to protected and conserved areas through equity \ufb01nancing or debt \ufb01nancing. The type of instrument needs to be adapted to the \ufb01nancing requirements, the nature of the underlying business, and risk appetite of the conservation project promoter and investor. If the project is generating or can generate a steady fow of cash or a product or service that is easily monetisable, a project \ufb01nancing structure with a loan can be suitable. Such a structure will allow partnership with an investor without their entering into the capital or governance of the project or conservation institution. Nevertheless, often loans are secured by certain guarantees and can carry high risks of foreclosure in case of repayment default. Therefore, it is important to balance the risks and rewards of a loan in terms of amount to be borrowed, activities to be \ufb01nanced and guarantees. Loans should always be used to \ufb01nance production activities which can generate assets to repay the debt. Carbon-asset backed loans seem very adapted to conservation \ufb01nance. If the business is high risk and the assets and cashfows to be generated are more uncertain, it may be better to have a capital equity investor putting their own capital in the venture, at their own risk. For new ventures which normally carry a much higher risk, an equity type of investor may be more suitable and be easier to get into business with. The downside is that the proponent will need to sell part of the company and may be diluted to a minority shareholder position. The upside is that proponents will have the resources needed to undertake the conservation venture! 42 Seed capital was provided by the US and Mexican governments and a group of US private philanthropic donors, and FMCN now manages an endowment of US$150 million, which is complemented by a stream of earmarked sinking funds raised from diverse sources at a rate of US$3-4 million per year. In 1996 FMCN was appointed manager of a separate endowment of US$16.48 million from GEF, the Fund for Natural Protected Areas (FANP). This is not a legal entity, but a fund which is segregated from FMCN\u2019s other programmes and established to originally support 10 national protected areas. It later received further capital from GEF to include 12 additional protected areas in the programme, contingent upon one-to-one matching funds. FANP surpassed the required match, and today supports the management of 50 of Mexico\u2019s 182 protected areas with an endowment of US$106 million with the contributions of 23 donors. By covering basic operational costs of the protected areas and capacity building, FANP has helped attract additional funds from both public and private sources. Furthermore, FANP has been able to customise disbursements to protected area needs, making them available at the time of the year when government resources are not. FANP provides some key lessons for setting up an environmental fund. First, it is an example of how diversi\ufb01ed revenue sources can be a source of strength \u2013 with FANP and government funding complementing each other\u2019s de\ufb01ciencies. Second, its role in encouraging stakeholder participation, particularly that of communities around the protected areas, shows how a CTF can strengthen civil society engagement in conservation. INVESTMENT AND RISK Alternatively, funding may be accessed by means of investment. Unlike donations, investments have the expectation of a return. Investors can channel funds to protected and conserved areas through equity \ufb01nancing or debt \ufb01nancing. The type of instrument needs to be adapted to the \ufb01nancing requirements, the nature of the underlying business, and risk appetite of the conservation project promoter and investor.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9dd2f3c8-046c-49be-a981-e0367afe868b": {"__data__": {"id_": "9dd2f3c8-046c-49be-a981-e0367afe868b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/becoming-conservation-entrepreneur", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Becoming a conservation entrepreneur", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/becoming-conservation-entrepreneur", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7d67c535b215e93eb8c8c6410137148c9bbd794578c24a22a6669211d1fee8ca"}, "2": {"node_id": "2348c289-e585-4c9b-84a5-3460b500783d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/becoming-c