ther participating organisations concerning the legal status of any country, territory, or area, or of its authorities, or concerning the delimitation of its frontiers or boundaries. The views expressed in this publication do not necessarily reflect those of IUCN or other participating organisations. IUCN is pleased to acknowledge the support of its Framework Partners who provide core funding: Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Denmark; Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland; Government of France and the French Development Agency (AFD); the Ministry of Environment, Republic of Korea; the Norwegian Agency for Development Cooperation (Norad); the Swedish International Development Cooperation Agency (Sida); the Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation (SDC) and the United States Department of State. This analysis was made possible in part through support provided by the Office of Gender Equality and Women\u2019s Empowerment (GenDev) of the the United States Agency for International Development (USAID), under the terms of Award No. AID-EGEE-IO-13-00004, the initiative AGENT \u2013 Advancing Gender in the Environment. It was prepared by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN). For information about AGENT or this study please contact gender[at]iucn.org Published by: IUCN, Gland, Switzerland Produced by: IUCN Human Rights in Conservation Team Copyright: \u00a9 2021 IUCN, International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources Reproduction of this publication for educational or other non-commercial purposes is authorised without prior written permission from the copyright holder provided the source is fully acknowledged. Reproduction of this publication for resale or other commercial purposes is prohibited without prior written permission of the copyright holder. Recommended IUCN (2021). Gender and national climate planning: gender citation: integration in the revised Nationally Determined Contributions. Gland, Switzerland: IUCN.", "start_cha