ies that included gender in their NDCs and those without is significant, meaning that Parties without gender inclusion emitted, on average, more than three times the amount of GHGs as the 69 Parties that included gender (Figure 6). While this marks a change from the 2016 data11, in which 81% of the emissions from 2012 were emitted by the 97 Parties that did not include gender (out of 162 analysed INDCs), notably, still some of the world\u2019s highest emitters \u2014 the United States, Russia, Japan, South Korea, Australia \u2014 do not include gender in their NDCs. Equitable solutions to climate change require all countries, particularly the world\u2019s highest emitters, to recognise gender as a critical dimension to creating effective climate action. Data source: IUCN, authors Graphic by Estudio Relativo for IUCN 10 \u2193 Introduction Annex Conclusions and recommendations Findings TC \u2190 625 GTCO2e per Party (3.2 times more) x 18 parties x 69 parties 193 GTCO2e per Party VS *Two parties were not included in this \ufb01 gure due to lack of data on GHG emissions. None of them includes gender in its NDC.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9d547823-d9f9-4c88-b266-d693a94d8ed9": {"__data__": {"id_": "9d547823-d9f9-4c88-b266-d693a94d8ed9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/gender-and-national-climate-planning", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Gender and national climate planning", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/gender-and-national-climate-planning", "Author": "International Union for Conse